{{Infobox document|document_name=Declaration of Independence|image=File:Declaration of Independence of Burma.jpg|image_size=|image_alt=|caption=|orig_lang_code=my|title_orig=လွတ်လပ်ရေးကြေညာစာတမ်း|date_created=|date_presented=|date_ratified=|date_effective={{start date and age|1948|1|4}}|date_repeal=|location_of_document=Rangoon, Burma (now Yangon, Myanmar)|commissioned=|writer=[[Thein Han]], [[Min Thu Wun]], [[Ohn Pe]] and [[Win Sein]]|signers=|media_type=|subject=|purpose=}}
The '''Burmese Declaration of Independence''' ({{lang-my|လွတ်လပ်ရေးကြေညာစာတမ်း}}) was officially promulgated on 4 January 1948, marking the end of British rule in Burma (now Myanmar). The date is now celebrated as [[Independence Day (Myanmar)|Independence Day]], a national gazetted holiday. The document was jointly penned by [[Thein Han]], [[Min Thu Wun]], [[Ohn Pe]] and Win Sein, and translated into English by [[Maung Maung]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=|title=Dr Maung Maung|last=Taylor|first=Robert H.|date=2003-08-01|publisher=Flipside Digital Content Company Inc.|year=|isbn=9789814515863|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> [[U Thant]], Khin Maung, and Khin Zaw.
== History == The Declaration of Independence was preceded by another Declaration of Independence, signed by [[Ba Maw]] on 1 August 1943.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.drbamawlibrary.org/documents-statements.asp|title=Dr. Ba Maw Library - Statements|website=www.drbamawlibrary.org|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> During [[World War II]], the Japanese government advanced its previously vague promise to grant Burma independence after the end of the war.<ref>[[John Toland (author)|John Toland]], ''[[The Rising Sun: The Decline and Fall of the Japanese Empire 1936-1945]]'' p 456 Random House New York 1970</ref> The Japanese felt that this would give the Burmese a real stake in an [[Axis Powers|Axis]] victory in the [[Second World War]], creating resistance against possible re-colonization by the western powers, and increased military and economic support from Burma for the Japanese war effort. A Burma Independence Preparatory Committee chaired by Ba Maw was formed 8 May 1943 and the nominally independent [[State of Burma]] was proclaimed on 1 August 1943 with Ba Maw as "Naingandaw Adipadi" ([[head of state]]) as well as prime minister.
