{{Infobox company | name = JAMS | former_name = Judicial Arbitration and Mediation Services | logo = Logo JAMS.gif | type = Private, Multinational | founder = Hon. H. Warren Knight (Ret.) | area_served = Worldwide | industry = Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR), Arbitration, Mediation | homepage = [https://www.jamsadr.com jamsadr.com] | location_city = [[Irvine, California]] | location_country = [[United States]] }}
'''JAMS''', formerly known as '''Judicial Arbitration and Mediation Services, Inc.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamsadr.com/about-the-jams-name/|title=About the JAMS Name|publisher=JAMS|accessdate=2014-04-07}}</ref> is a [[United States]]-based for-profit organization of [[alternative dispute resolution]] (ADR) services, including [[mediation]] and [[arbitration]].<ref name=berner-grow /><ref name=drahozal-zyontz-2012>{{cite journal|last=Drahozal|first=Christopher R.|last2=Zyontz|first2=Samantha|title=Private Regulation of Consumer Arbitration|journal=Tennessee Law Review|date=Winter 2012|volume=79|issue=2|pages=289–352}}</ref> H. Warren Knight, a former [[California Superior Court]] judge, founded JAMS in 1979 in [[Santa Ana, California]].<ref name=knight-biography>{{cite web|title=Hon H. Warren Knight (Ret.), Founder|url=http://www.jamsadr.com/knight/|publisher=JAMS|accessdate=6 April 2014}}</ref> A 1994 merger with Endispute of Washington, D.C. made JAMS into the largest private arbitration and mediation service in the country.<ref>{{cite news | last=Gomez | first=James M. | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-05-25/business/fi-61919_1_alternative-dispute | title=Mediation Succeeds, There's No Argument: Negotiating: JAMS of Orange uses retired judges to help disputants settle cases out of court, saving fees, time, trouble. | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=May 25, 1994 | accessdate=2014-04-07 }}</ref> It is one of the major arbitration administration organizations in the United States.{{#tag:ref|A 2008 ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' article described JAMS and the American Arbitration Association as the main competitors of the National Arbitration Forum in the field of arbitration.<ref name=berner-grow>{{cite web|last=Berner|first=Robert|last2=Grow|first2=Brian|title=Banks vs. Consumers (Guess Who Wins)|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2008-06-04/banks-vs-dot-consumers-guess-who-wins|work=Businessweek|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=17 January 2014|date=2008-06-04}}</ref> The [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]]'s preliminary study on arbitration stated that there was consensus that JAMS and the American Arbitration Association were the leading arbitration administration organizations in the United States.<ref name=cfpb-arbitration-preliminary>{{cite web|title=Arbitration Study Preliminary Results: Section 1028(a) Study Results To Date|url=http://files.consumerfinance.gov/f/201312_cfpb_arbitration-study-preliminary-results.pdf|accessdate=12 December 2013|author=[[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]]|date=2013-12-12}}</ref>{{rp|60}}|group=nb|name=note-main-organization}} As of 2017, JAMS has 27 resolution centers, including its headquarters in [[Irvine, California]] and centers in [[Toronto]] and [[London]].<ref name=jams-resolution-centers>{{cite web|title=JAMS Resolution Centers|url=http://www.jamsadr.com/locations/|publisher=JAMS|accessdate=6 April 2014}}</ref> JAMS specializes in mediating and arbitrating complex, multi-party, business/commercial cases.
{{Asof|2012|post=,}} JAMS administers a few hundred [[consumer arbitration]] cases per year.<ref name=sternlight-2012>{{cite journal|last=Sternlight|first=Jean R.|title=Mandatory Binding Arbitration Clauses Prevent Consumers from Presenting Procedurally Difficult Claims|journal=Southwestern Law Review|year=2012|volume=42|pages=87–129|url=http://www.swlaw.edu/pdfs/lr/42_1sternlight.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|99}} JAMS's Consumer Minimum Standards have been the subject of scholarly commentary.<ref name=kaplinsky-levin-1999>{{cite journal|last=Kaplinsky|first=Alan S.|last2=Levin|first2=Mark J.|title=Consumer Financial Services Arbitration: Last Year's Trend Has Become this Year's Mainstay|journal=[[The Business Lawyer]]|date=May 1999|volume=54|issue=3|pages=1405–1418}}</ref>{{rp|1407–08}}<ref name=drahozal-zyontz-2012 />{{rp|305–06}} A policy promulgated by JAMS in 2004 that would have allowed for class arbitrations, even if the arbitration agreement did not allow them, and the subsequent retraction of that policy, were also the subject of controversy.<ref name=kaplinsky-levin-jams>{{cite journal|last=Kaplinsky|first=Alan S.|last2=Levin|first2=Mark J.|title=Is JAMS in a Jam Over Its Policy Regarding Class Action Waivers in Consumer Arbitration Agreements?|journal=The Business Lawyer|date=February 2006|volume=61|issue=2|pages=923–929}}</ref><ref name=gilles-2005>{{cite journal|last=Gilles|first=Myriam|title=Opting Out of Liability: The Forthcoming, Near-Total Demise of the Modern Class Action|journal=Michigan Law Review|date=December 2005|volume=104|pages=373–430 [397]|url=http://www.michiganlawreview.org/assets/pdfs/104/3/Gilles.pdf|accessdate=2 March 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116071709/http://www.michiganlawreview.org/assets/pdfs/104/3/Gilles.pdf|archivedate=16 January 2013|df=}}</ref>
==JAMS Foundation== {{Unreferenced section|date=May 2018}} JAMS established the '''JAMS Foundation''' to offer financial assistance for [[conflict resolution]] initiatives with national or international impact and to share its [[dispute resolution]] experience and expertise for the benefit of the public interest.{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}} Funded entirely by contributions from JAMS neutrals and staff{{Citation needed|reason=source needed that that's the entire funding source|date=October 2013}}, the '''JAMS Foundation''' has provided nearly $5 million in grants for [[conflict resolution]] initiatives.{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}} The JAMS Foundation also established the '''Weinstein International Fellowship Program''' to provide opportunities for individuals from outside the United States to visit the U.S. and learn more about [[dispute resolution]] processes and practices and to pursue a project of their own to advance [[dispute resolution]] in their home countries. The Foundation, through the Warren Knight Award, has awarded $25,000 grants to programs dedicated to resolving conflict both in the US and around the world.{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}}
